#X text 59 24 [superosc~] is a general wave stacking object. By default you have 7 detuned sawtooth waves and is inspired by JP-8000's supersaw oscillator. This is avery complex and versatile object where you can set from 1 to 16 oscillators. You should check all the features in the help file. The example below shows different waveforms., f 72;
#X text 348 120 There's also a rigthmost inlet for syncing the phases of the oscillators in different modes. By default it syncs to random phases., f 32;
#X obj 385 402 superosc~ -midi 0 0 25, f 9;
#X obj 340 231 vradio 19 1 0 4 empty empty empty 0 -10 0 12 #dfdfdf #000000 #000000 0;
#X msg 340 317 syncmode \$1;
#X text 59 476 mode 3: sync all phases to 0, f 36;
#X text 116 530 Really \, do check the help file for more details!, f 23;
#X text 651 66 Here's a simplified version of the default object \, which also has gain and spread settings. Here we have sawtooth waves with initial phases set to zero. The detuning in cents is multiplied by a list of 7 detuning ratios \, which is then multiplied to the frequency input. The [bl.saw~] then generates 7 channels with each frequency value. The [mix~] object comes in handy to downmix this to a stereo output with a fixed list of gains and it also takes fixed panning positions for each oscillator., f 45;
